evaluation.response:
It sounds like you're facing quite the abrupt change in pace and these feelings of frustration you're experiencing are normal. But here are a few things you might consider that could help make this recovery time a bit easier:

*   **Stay organized**: You could try using a calendar to schedule your healing process and any follow-up appointments.&#x20;
*   **Movie nights**: Select your favorite movies or TV shows and have your mom plan movie nights where you can both enjoy each other's company.
*   **Thank you cards**: You could write thank you cards to those who have visited you while you recover.&#x20;
*   **Meal planning**: Involving your mom in meal planning and prep could also help you feel more engaged. Here are a few low-key meals you could make:&#x20;
    *   [Low-Effort Chicken Salad](https://res.freecodecamp.org/forum/t/low-effort-chicken-salad/710067) (Fast, healthy, and easy to customize.)
    *   [Five-Minute Gluten-Free Pizza](https://res.freecodecamp.org/forum/t/five-minute-gluten-free-pizza/712096) (Perfect for when you need a quick, stress-free meal.)
    *   [Creamy Rice Porridge](https://res.freecodecamp.org/forum/t/creamy-rice-porridge/720121) (Quick and efficient meal that can be made using a handheld electric mixer)

The recovery phase after surgery can present its own set of challenges, but you can utilize this time for reflection and personal growth, and finding ways to maintain your independence can be key for your own emotional and psychological well-being.
